{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Kuno Meyer | image = K meyer.jpg | imagesize =155px | caption = Kuno Meyer | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1858|12|20}} | birth_place = [[Hamburg]], Germany | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1919|10|11|1858|12|20}} | death_place = [[Leipzig]], Germany | occupation = [[Academia|Academic]] | nationality = German }}
'''Kuno Meyer''' (20 December 1858 – 11 October 1919) was a German scholar, distinguished in the field of [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] philology and literature. His pro-German stance at the start of [[World War I]] in the United States was a source of controversy. His brother was the distinguished classical scholar, [[Eduard Meyer]].
Meyer was considered first and foremost a lexicographer among Celtic scholars but is known by the general public in Ireland rather as the man who introduced them to ''Selections from Ancient Irish Poetry'' (1911).<ref name=murphy/>{{sfnp|Best|1923|p=182}}
He founded and edited four journals devoted to Celtic Studies,{{sfnp|Best|1923|p=182}} published numerous texts and translations of Old and Middle Irish romances and sagas, and wrote prolifically, his topics ranging to name origins and ancient law.<ref name=titley/>
==Early life== Born in [[Hamburg]], he studied there at the [[Gelehrtenschule of the Johanneum]].<ref>{{Cite Americana|wstitle=Meyer, Kuno |year=1920}}</ref> He spent two years in [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]], as a teenager (1874–1876) learning [[English language|English]].{{sfnp|Ó Lúing|1991|p=1}}<ref name=murphy/>
From 1879, he attended the [[University of Leipzig]], where he was taught Celtic scholarship by [[Ernst Windisch]]. He received his doctorate for his thesis ''Eine irische Version der Alexandersage'', an Irish version of the [[Alexander Romance]], in 1884.<ref name=meyer-thesis/>
==Lecturer== He then took up the post of lecturer in [[Teutonic languages]] at the new University College, [[Liverpool]], the precursor of the [[University of Liverpool]], which was established three years earlier.<ref name=collier>{{Cite Collier's|wstitle=Meyer, Kuno|year=1921}}</ref>
He continued to publish on [[Old Irish language|Old Irish]] and more general topics on the [[Celtic languages]] , as well as producing textbooks for [[German language|German]]. In 1896, he founded and edited jointly with {{illm|Ludwig Stern{{!}}Ludwig Christian Stern|de|Ludwig Stern}}, the prestigious ''[[Zeitschrift für celtische Philologie]]''. He also cofounded ''Archiv für celtische Lexicographie'' in 1898 with [[Whitley Stokes]], producing 3 volumes from 1900 to 1907.{{sfnp|Ó Lúing|1991|pp=21, 249}}
In 1903, Meyer founded the [[School of Irish Learning]] in Dublin, and the next year created its journal ''[[Ériu (journal)|Ériu]]'' of which he was the editor. Also in 1904, he became Todd Professor in the Celtic Languages at the [[Royal Irish Academy]]. In October 1911, he followed [[Heinrich Zimmer (Celticist)|Heinrich Zimmer]] as Professor of Celtic Philology at [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Friedrich Wilhelm University]] in Berlin; the following year, a volume of ''Miscellany'' was presented to him by pupils and friends in honour of his election, and he was made a freeman of both [[Dublin]] and [[Cork (city)|Cork]].{{sfnp|Ó Lúing|1991|pp=172–3}}
==First World War== At the outbreak of the [[First World War]], Meyer left Europe for the United States of America, where he lectured at [[Columbia University]], [[University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign|University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]], and elsewhere.{{efn|{{Harvnb|Ó Lúing|1991|p=169}}: "{{illm|Gertrude Schoepperle|de|Gertrude Schoepperle}} had arranged for a long stay at Urbana University in Illinois".}}{{sfnp|Ó Lúing|1991|pp=168–9}} A pro-German speech he gave in December 1914 to [[Clan na Gael]] on [[Long Island]] caused outrage in Britain and some factions among the Irish,<!--Ó Lúing (1991) pp.170–3--> and as a result, he was removed from the roll of freemen in Dublin and Cork and from his Honorary Professorship of Celtic at Liverpool. He also resigned as Director of the School of Irish Learning and editor of ''Ériu''.{{sfnp|Ó Lúing|1991|pp=170–3, 178–9}}
[[Harvard University]] also had extended an invitation to Meyer to lecture on campus, but it subsequently "disinvited" him on in the fall of 1914 on account of Meyer's propagandist activity.<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=Harvard Alumni Bulletin |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JyTPAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA544 |title=A War Poem and Its Consequences |pages=235–6|volume=17|number=30|date=5 May 1915}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Bethell |first=John T. |title=Harvard Observed: An Illustrated History of the University in the Twentieth Century |publisher=Harvard University Press |year=1998 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hxpvsfxjfMAC&pg=PA70 |page=70}}</ref>
Meyer nevertheless accepted candidacy for the post of exchange professor at Harvard, at the recommendation of German professors there. However, when the April 1915 issue of ''[[The Harvard Advocate]]'' awarded first prize to an anti-German satirical poem "Gott mit Uns" written by an undergraduate, Meyer sent the university (and the press) a letter of protest, rebuking the faculty members who served as judges for failure to exercise neutrality. Meyer also declined his candidacy from the exchange professorship in the letter. In a reply, President [[Abbott Lawrence Lowell]] said, in explaining Harvard's policy, that freedom of speech includes pro-German and pro-Allied voices alike.<ref>{{EB1922|wstitle=Lowell, Abbott Lawrence|inline=1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|journal=The Harvard graduates' magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uj4BAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA235|title=The Meyer incident|pages=235–6|volume=24|number=93|date=September 1915|accessdate=31 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=collier/>
==Later life== He was injured in a railway collision in 1915 and met 27-year-old Florence Lewis while he was recovering in a California hospital. They married shortly afterwards.{{sfnp|Ó Lúing|1991|pp=195, 212}}<ref>http://www.ucc.ie/celt/meyer.html</ref> Florence went to Germany in 1916, Meyer in 1917. In 1919 Florence and her daughter went to Switzerland. He died in [[Leipzig]].
==Legacy== Posthumously, in 1920, Meyer's name was restored, both by Dublin and Cork, in their Rolls of Honorary Freemen. The restoration happened on 19 April 1920 in Dublin, where [[Sinn Féin]] had won control of the City Council three months before, rescinding the decision taken in 1915 by the [[Irish Parliamentary Party]].<ref>[http://www.dublincity.ie/main-menu-services-press-and-news-read-press-release-press-releases-2013-press-releases-november-0 Freedom of the City of Dublin]</ref>
In 1965, the Gaelic League and the ''Irish Press'' petitioned the restoration as they were unaware that it had already occurred.<ref name=murphy/>
Meyer was regranted the Freedom of the City of Cork, as follows: "Re-elected 14th May, 1920, and order of Council of the 8th January, 1915, expunging his name from the roll rescinded."<ref>[http://www.corkcity.ie/yourcouncil/freedomofthecity/ Your Council » Freedom of the City]</ref>
Also in 1920, Meyer was described by his acquaintance [[Douglas Hyde]], Celtic philologist and later president of the Republic of Ireland, as "one of the most lovable men who ever existed, and himself undoubtedly in love with Ireland". Hyde credited him with advancing the goals of the [[Gaelic League]] when the question arose whether to allow the teaching of the Irish language in the Intermediate Education of Ireland. <ref name="hyde">{{citation|last=Hyde |first=Douglas |author-link=Douglas Hyde |title=Canon Peter O'Leary and Dr. Kuno Meyer |journal=Studies: An Irish Quarterly Review |volume=9 |number=34 |date=June 1920 |pages=297–301 |jstor=30082987}}</ref>
[[W. T. Cosgrave]], later president of the [[Irish Free State]], as a Dublin councilman, had strenuously opposed removal of Meyer's name from Dublin's Freemen roll in the first place. Cosgrave wrote in a letter that Meyer was recognized as "the greatest Celtic authority since the death of [[Whitley Stokes]]" and that he has "done more for Irish scholarship and Irish national glory than any other living man".<ref name="cosgrave">{{cite journal|ref=harv|last=Cosgrave |first=W. T. |author-link=W. T. Cosgrave |title=Kuno Meyer |journal=The Vital Issue (Issues and Events) |volume=3 |number=3 |date=17 July 1915 |page=5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0no-AQAAMAAJ&pg=PR23 |accessdate=2018-11-16}} (reprint of Cosgrave's letter dated 8 February 1915)</ref>{{sfnp|Ó Lúing|1991|pp=173, 175}}
In 2004, on the centenary of the publication of ''Ériu'', Proinsias Mac Cana described Kuno Meyer as "great" scholar, in "brilliant" partnership with [[John Strachan (linguist)|John Strachan]] as the first editors of ''Ériu'', his predecessors in that position. Meyer is among those credited with playing a crucial role in fostering native Irish Celtists in the initial phases of ''Ériu'' and the School of Irish Learning, and when the editorship over ''Ériu'' later passed to the succeeding generation of Irish scholars, tantamount to the fulfillment of the "primary intention of Meyer and his associates".{{r|"mac cana"}}
